                                    <div class="faq-section" style="margin-top: 40px;">
                                        <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
                                        <h3>How much does it cost to build a healthcare app in India in 2026?</h3>
                                        <p>MVP patient app: &#8377;8L–&#8377;12L. Telemedicine app with video: &#8377;15L–&#8377;22L. Full healthcare ecosystem with EHR + ABDM: &#8377;25L–&#8377;40L. Enterprise hospital-grade platform: &#8377;45L+. Add 15–25% for HIPAA + DPDP compliance budget.</p>
                                        <h3>What is ABDM and is it mandatory for healthcare apps in India?</h3>
                                        <p>ABDM (Ayushman Bharat Digital Mission) is India's national health-data interoperability layer. ABHA-linking and FHIR-compliant record exchange are not legally mandatory yet for private apps but are de facto expected by 2026 for partner-clinic flows, insurance integrations and government health programmes. Most serious healthtech apps now ship ABDM-ready.</p>
                                        <h3>Do I need HIPAA compliance for an India-only healthcare app?</h3>
                                        <p>Not strictly — HIPAA is a US framework. India's DPDP Act and ABDM/NDHM guidelines apply instead. But many Indian healthtech apps build to HIPAA standards anyway because (a) it's a stronger baseline than DPDP currently, (b) it future-proofs you for US partnerships, and (c) hospitals and insurance partners increasingly ask for it.</p>
                                        <h3>How long does it take to build a telemedicine app?</h3>
                                        <p>10–14 weeks for a full telemedicine app with patient + doctor apps, video consultation engine, e-prescription, payments and basic EHR. Add 4–6 weeks for ABDM integration and HIPAA-grade compliance audit.</p>
                                        <h3>What's the difference between a telemedicine app and an EHR?</h3>
                                        <p>A telemedicine app handles consultation flow (booking, video, prescription, follow-up). An EHR (Electronic Health Record) is the longitudinal patient record — labs, vitals, allergies, medications, history. Modern healthcare apps usually combine both: telemed flow on the front-end, EHR data layer behind it, with FHIR APIs as the integration standard.</p>
